'''Nabil Bentaleb''' ({{langx|ar|نَبِيل بْن طَالِب}}; born 24 November 1994) is a professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[defensive midfielder]] for {{French football updater|Lille}} club [[Lille OSC|Lille]]. Born in France, he plays for the [[Algeria national football team|Algeria national team]].

Bentaleb began his senior career with [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] in 2013 and later played for [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]], [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] and [[Angers SCO|Angers]] before joining his hometown club Lille in 2023. He made his senior international debut in March 2014 and has represented Algeria at the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] and the [[Africa Cup of Nations]] in [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations|2015]], [[2017 Africa Cup of Nations|2017]] and [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations|2023]].

==Club career==
===Early career===
Born in [[Lille]] to Algerian parents from [[Mostaganem]], Bentaleb started his career at the academy of local side, [[Lille OSC|Lille]].<ref name="Five Facts">{{cite web|last=Coombs|first=Dan|title=Five facts about Tottenham's under-21 hero Nabil Bentaleb|url=http://hereisthecity.com/en-gb/2013/04/24/five-facts-about-tottenhams-under-21-hero-nabil-bentaleb/|work=Here is the City|access-date=22 December 2013}}</ref> However, he was released from the academy at the age of 15 and then went to [[Belgium]] to play for [[R.E. Mouscron|Mouscron]].<ref name="Five Facts"/> Bentaleb then went on trial with [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] before eventually signing into the academy of [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] in January 2012.<ref name="Five Facts"/>  During the 2012–13 season, Bentaleb broke into the under-21 side at Tottenham and scored four goals in fourteen matches, including the winning goal against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]'s [[Arsenal F.C. Academy|Academy]].<ref name="New Deal 2013">{{cite web|title=NEW DEAL FOR NABIL|url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/new-deal-for-nabil-211013/|work=Tottenham Hotspur Football Club|access-date=22 December 2013}}</ref> His performance that season earned him a new four-year contract at Tottenham Hotspur until 2018.<ref name="New Deal 2013"/>

===Tottenham Hotspur===
On 22 December 2013, Bentaleb was selected into the 18-man first-team squad for [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] in a [[2013–14 Premier League|Premier League]] match against [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].<ref name="SOU 2-3 TOTT">{{cite web|title=SOUTHAMPTON VS. TOTTENHAM HOTSPUR 2 – 3|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2013/12/22/england/premier-league/southampton-fc/tottenham-hotspur-football-club/1483622/|work=Soccerway|access-date=22 December 2013}}</ref> He made his professional debut in that match when he came on as a [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in the 50th minute for [[Mousa Dembélé (Belgian footballer)|Mousa Dembélé]], Tottenham won the match 3–2.<ref name="SOU 2-3 TOTT"/> His first start for Spurs came in the [[North London derby]] against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in the third round of the [[2013–14 FA Cup|FA Cup]] on 4 January.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/451999/TEAMS-Fabianski-Rosicky-Vermaelen-Gnabry-in-for-Arsenal-Bentaleb-starts-for-Spurs|title=TEAMS: Fabianski, Rosicky, Vermaelen & Gnabry in for Arsenal; Bentaleb starts for Spurs|date=4 January 2015|work=Daily Express}}</ref> Bentaleb scored his first goal for the club on 17 December 2014 in the fifth round of the [[2014–15 Football League Cup|Football League Cup]] against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/30407770|title=Tottenham 4–0 Newcastle|access-date=2 March 2015|work=BBC}}</ref>

On 1 March 2015, Bentaleb started for Tottenham in the [[2015 Football League Cup Final]], a match they lost 2–0 to [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/mar/01/chelsea-tottenham-capital-one-cup-final-player-ratings|title=Chelsea 2–0 Tottenham Hotspur: Capital One Cup final player ratings|access-date=2 March 2015|work=The Guardian}}</ref> On 6 July, he signed a new five-year contract.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/new-deal-for-nabil-060715/|title=New deal for Nabil|access-date=7 July 2015|work=Tottenham Hotspurs F.C.}}</ref>

===Schalke 04===
On 25 August 2016, Bentaleb joined [[Bundesliga]] side [[Schalke 04]] on a season-long loan deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.schalke04.de/en/news/160825_bentaleb/page/2419--86-86-0.html|title=S04 agree season-long loan deal for Nabil Bentaleb|publisher=FC Schalke 04|date=25 August 2016|access-date=25 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826163648/http://www.schalke04.de/en/news/160825_bentaleb/page/2419--86-86-0.html|archive-date=26 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> He went on to make his debut in an away match against [[Eintracht Frankfurt|Frankfurt]] two days later, which Schalke lost 1–0.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/frankfurt-vs-schalke/teams/360223 |title=Eintracht Frankfurt 1 – 0 Schalke |publisher=Sky Sports |date=27 August 2016 |access-date=6 September 2016 }}</ref> His first start came the next weekend against [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern]], after which Bentaleb became a fixture in new manager [[Markus Weinzierl]]'s starting eleven. Enduring Schalke's worst ever start to a Bundesliga with five consecutive losses,<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://worldsoccertalk.com/2016/09/25/schalke-suffer-worst-ever-bundesliga-start/ |title=Schalke suffer worst ever Bundesliga start |location=[[Berlin]] |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |date=25 September 2016}}</ref> Bentaleb confirmed his desire to remain in [[Gelsenkirchen]], saying that "at Schalke they believe in me", while also appreciating the fans' ability to stick beside a team going through a rough patch in comparison to English fans.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sportbild.bild.de/bundesliga/vereine/bundesliga/schalke-zugang-bentaleb-wir-haben-genug-malocht-48131658.sport.html |title=Schalke-Zugang Bentaleb: "Wir haben genug malocht" |work=Sport Bild |first=Robert |last=Hiersemann |language=de |trans-title=Schalke-acquisition Bentaleb: "We've sweated away enough" |date=5 October 2016}}</ref>

On 15 October, Bentaleb came through with his first goal for Schalke, a strike from distance that put them temporarily ahead of [[FC Augsburg|Augsburg]] in a 1–1 draw. This was the first goal reviewed by [[goal-line technology]] in the Bundesliga to be successfully allowed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bild.de/bundesliga/1-liga/saison-2016-2017/spielbericht-fc-augsburg-gegen-fc-schalke-04-am-7-Spieltag-46904210.bild.html |title=Schalke-Tor dank Schiri-Uhr |work=Bild |first1=Dennis |last1=Amedovski |first2=Kristina |last2=Ellwanger |first3=Sebastian |last3=Hochrainer |date=15 October 2016}}</ref> In Schalke's next match, he scored twice against [[1. FSV Mainz 05|Mainz]] in a 3–0 victory, becoming the first Algerian to achieve the feat in Bundesliga play.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/account/suspended|title=Twitter / Account Suspended|website=twitter.com}}</ref> Immediately after the match, a report<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bild.de/sport/fussball/christian-heidel/hat-ihn-bis-2021-sicher-48436470.bild.html |title=Schalke hält Knaller Bentaleb |work=Bild |first1=Sebastian |last1=Hochrainer |first2=Marc |last2=Siekmann |first3=Peter |last3=Wenzel |language=de |trans-title=Schalke keeps banger Bentaleb |date=24 October 2016}}</ref> emerged claiming that Bentaleb had already signed a four-year contract to remain with Schalke, which would go in effect after a permanent buying option in his loan deal was picked up, putting his future at [[White Hart Lane]] in question.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.com/story/2982552/schalke-hint-at-permanent-deal-to-sign-tottenhams-nabil-bentaleb |title=Schalke hint at permanent deal to sign Tottenham's Nabil Bentaleb |work=ESPN FC |first=Stephan |last=Uersfeld |date=27 October 2016}}</ref>

On 24 February 2017, Tottenham Hotspur announced that they had reached an agreement with Schalke 04 for Bentaleb's transfer to be made permanent at the end of the loan period.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bentaleb to join Schalke on permanent deal|url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/bentaleb-to-join-schalke-on-permanent-deal-240217/|publisher=Tottenham Hotspur Ltd|access-date=24 February 2017|date=24 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Nabil Bentaleb: Schalke to sign Tottenham midfielder on four-year deal|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39083959|access-date=24 February 2017|work=BBC Sport|date=24 February 2017}}</ref>

In March 2019 he was demoted to Schalke's under-23 team, "due to disciplinary reasons".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47606243|title=Nabil Bentaleb: Algeria international disciplined by Schalke|date=18 March 2019|website=BBC Sport|access-date=27 August 2019}}</ref> He returned to the first-team in April 2019,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47854304|title=Algeria's Nabil Bentaleb to rejoin Schalke first-team squad|date=8 April 2019|website=BBC Sport|access-date=27 August 2019|first=Mohamed Fajah|last=Barrie}}</ref> before being dropped to the second team again later that month.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48054824|title=Nabil Bentaleb: Algeria international disciplined by Schalke for second time|date=25 April 2019|website=BBC Sport|access-date=27 August 2019|first=Mohamed Fajah|last=Barrie}}</ref>

===Newcastle United===
On 21 January 2020, Bentaleb signed on loan with [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] for the remainder of the [[2019–20 Premier League]] season with the club having the option to make the deal permanent. Bentaleb made his debut in a 0–0 draw against Oxford United in the fourth round of the FA Cup. Bentaleb returned to Schalke at the end of the season after not impressing on loan.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nufc.co.uk/news/latest-news/magpies-sign-nabil-bentaleb-on-loan/ |title=Magpies sign Nabil Bentaleb on loan |work=Newcastle United F.C. |first=Dan |last=King |date=21 January 2020 |access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref>

===Angers===
On 6 January 2022, Bentaleb signed for French club [[Angers SCO|Angers]] who play in [[Ligue 1]], on a two-and-a-half-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.angers-sco.fr/nabil-bentaleb-est-angevin/|title=Nabil Bentaleb est Angevin !|website=www.angers-sco.fr|language=French|date=6 January 2022}}</ref>

===Lille===
On 28 August 2023, Bentaleb joined his hometown team [[Lille OSC]] on a three-year deal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Transferts-nabil-bentaleb-angers-debarque-enfin-a-lille/1416247|title=Transferts : Nabil Bentaleb (Angers) débarque enfin à Lille|trans-title=Transfers: Nabil Bentaleb (Angers) finally arrives in Lille|language=fr|publisher=L'Équipe|date=28 August 2023|access-date=28 August 2023}}</ref> In his first season at the French club, Bentaleb amassed 26 appearances as Lille finished fourth.<ref>{{cite web | title=Summary - Nabil Bentaleb - Results, fixtures, squad, statistics, photos, videos - Soccerway | url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/nabil-bentaleb/232390/ }}</ref> However, after the season, in June 2024, Bentaleb suffered a cardiac arrest and was told his career might be over.<ref>{{cite web | title=The astounding return of Algeria's Bentaleb, eight months after heart attack | date=18 February 2025 | url=https://www.espn.in/espn/story/_/id/43897064/the-astounding-return-algeria-nabil-bentaleb-eight-months-heart-attack }}</ref>

After over seven months out of action, Bentaleb was cleared to return to competitive football by the French Football Federation on 12 February 2025. He made his return to football on 16 February 2025, coming on as a 76th minute substitute against [[Stade Rennais FC|Rennes]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Lille 2-0 Rennes (Feb 16, 2025) Final Score | url=https://www.espn.com/football/match/_/gameId/706620 }}</ref> Bentaleb went on to score four minutes into his return, and celebrated by running to the Lille bench, where he was mobbed by his team-mates and coaching staff. Speaking about the goal, Lille boss [[Bruno Genesio]] proclaimed that the story behind it was "worthy of a film".<ref>{{cite web | title=Nabil Bentaleb: Lille midfielder scores on return from cardiac arrest | date=16 February 2025 | url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c04n4n124wro }}</ref>

==International career==
On 14 November 2012, Bentaleb made his debut for [[France national under-19 football team|France U19]] in a friendly match, coming on as a half-time substitute in a 3–0 loss to [[Germany national under-19 football team|Germany U19]].

Despite having represented France, he was courted by the [[Algerian Football Federation]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Tottenham's Bentaleb under Algeria's radar|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/6/54/91221/Sports/Africa/Tottenhams-Bentaleb-under-Algerias-radar-.aspx|publisher=ahram.org.eg|access-date=28 January 2014|date=9 January 2014}}</ref> and accepted its offer.<ref>{{cite web|author=Algeria |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/algeria/10602900/World-Cup-2014-A-change-in-eligibility-criteria-has-seen-Algeria-grow-stronger-and-stronger.html |title=World Cup 2014: A change in eligibility criteria has seen Algeria grow stronger and stronger |date=28 January 2014 |publisher=Telegraph |access-date=1 February 2014}}</ref> In January 2014, Tottenham Hotspur manager [[Tim Sherwood]] suggested that the [[The Football Association|English Football Association]] were also interested.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tim Sherwood warns of French attempts to poach Tottenham's Nabil Bentaleb|url=http://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/455046/Tim-Sherwood-warns-of-French-attempts-to-poach-Tottenham-s-Nabil-Bentaleb|publisher=express.co.uk|access-date=28 January 2014|date=21 January 2014}}</ref> However, Bentaleb would not meet the requirements to play for England under the unique rules set out in the [[Home Nations' gentlemen's agreement|Home Nations agreement]]. The Home Nations agreement requires that players engage in a minimum of five years of education before the age of 18 within the territory of the relevant association and does not offer national team eligibility through residency.<ref>{{cite web |title=Swansea City defender Angel Rangel ineligible for Wales |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/18833190 |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=13 July 2012 |access-date=6 October 2013 }}</ref>

On 15 February 2014, Bentaleb pledged his international future to [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/26210860 |title=BBC Sport – Bentaleb pledges international future to Algeria |work=BBC Sport |date=15 February 2014 |publisher=Bbc.com |access-date=15 February 2014}}</ref> A few days later, he was called up by Algeria coach [[Vahid Halilhodžić]] for a friendly match against [[Slovenia national football team|Slovenia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.dzfoot.com/2014/02/nabil-bentaleb-and-zinedine-ferhat-receive-first-call-ups-for-slovenia-friendly/|title=Nabil Bentaleb and Zinedine Ferhat receive first call-ups for Slovenia friendly|author=Walid Z.|publisher=DZFoot|date=17 February 2014|access-date=17 February 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222101022/http://en.dzfoot.com/2014/02/nabil-bentaleb-and-zinedine-ferhat-receive-first-call-ups-for-slovenia-friendly/|archive-date=22 February 2014}}</ref> He made his debut on 5 March, playing the full game in a 2–0 win over Slovenia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2014/03/05/world/friendlies/algeria/slovenia/1625790/|title=Algeria vs. Slovenia – 5 March 2014 – Soccerway|work=soccerway.com}}</ref> He scored his first goal for his country against [[Romania national football team|Romania]] on 4 June 2014 at the [[Stade de Genève]] in [[Switzerland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.101greatgoals.com/blog/tottenhams-nabil-bentaleb-scores-his-1st-algeria-goal-after-a-terrible-error-from-man-city-goalie-costel-pantilimon/ |title=Tottenham's Nabil Bentaleb scores his 1st Algeria goal after a terrible error from Man City goalie Costel Pantilimon |date=4 June 2014|access-date=5 June 2014}}</ref>

In June 2014, Bentaleb was named in Algeria's 23-man squad for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/algeria/10810473/Algeria-World-Cup-2014-squad.html|title=Algeria World Cup 2014 squad|date=2 June 2014|access-date=18 June 2014|work=The Telegraph}}</ref> He started in midfield for the team's opening match of the tournament – a 2–1 defeat by [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] in [[Belo Horizonte]] on 17 June.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/25285127|title=Belgium 2–1 Algeria|date=17 June 2014|access-date=18 June 2014|work=BBC}}</ref> He also played the full ninety minutes for ''Les Fennecs'' in their two other [[2014 FIFA World Cup Group H|Group H]] matches; a 4–2 victory over [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]] and a 1–1 draw with [[Russia national football team|Russia]]. However, he was an unused substitute during the team's 2–1 defeat to [[Germany national football team|Germany]] in the [[2014 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Germany vs Algeria|round of 16]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/dec/18/algeria-nabil-bentaleb-tottenham-spurs|title=Algeria call will interrupt progress of Nabil Bentaleb at Tottenham|date=18 December 2014|access-date=15 January 2015|work=The Guardian}}</ref> On 15 December 2014, Bentaleb was named in Algeria's 23-man squad for the [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations]] in [[Equatorial Guinea]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fifa.com/world-match-centre/news/newsid/249/305/5/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115134816/http://www.fifa.com/world-match-centre/news/newsid/249/305/5/|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 January 2015|title=Gourcuff names Algeria squad for Africa Cup of Nations|date=15 December 2014|access-date=15 January 2015|work=FIFA}}</ref>

In December 2023, he was named in Algeria's squad for the [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.algerie-focus.com/can-2024-lalgerie-devoile-sa-liste-officielle-qui-sont-les-fennecs-prets-a-conquerir-lafrique/|title=CAN 2024 : L'Algérie Dévoile sa Liste Officielle – Qui Sont les Fennecs Prêts à Conquérir l'Afrique ?|language=French|date=30 December 2023|access-date=12 January 2024|publisher=Algérie-Focus}}</ref> On 31 May 2026, he was called up for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/bentaleb-back-algeria-world-cup-squad-named-2026-05-31/ |title=Bentaleb back for Algeria as World Cup squad named |publisher=Reuters |date=31 May 2026 }}</ref>

